 of global leadership will face challenges in the future, as it has in other realms of international competition. American Universities in a Global Market addresses the variety of issues crucial to understanding this preeminence and this challenge. The book examines the various factors that contributed to America’s success in higher education, including openness to people and ideas, generous governmental support, and a tradition of decentralized friendly competition. It also explores the advantages of holding a dominant position in this marketplace and examines the current state of American higher education in a comparative context, placing particular emphasis on how market forces affect universities. By discussing the differences in quality among students and institutions around the world, this volume sheds light on the singular aspects of American higher education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCompetition, International. 0aEducation and globalization. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  auniversity, college, higher education, united states of america, usa, american culture, public policy, globalization, global market, economics, law, research, international competition, governmental support, scientists, science, doctorate, doctoral students, postdoctoral studies, graduate student, overseas programs, career patterns, expansion, europe, china, korea, academics, academy, india.1 aAdams, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBettinger, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Grant C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorghans, Lex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBound, John, econt